T1  - Managers At Work: A Large-Scale Study Of The Managerial Job in New York City Government
AU  - Allan, Peter
Y1  - 1981/09/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255579
DO  - 10.5465/255579
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 613
EP  - 619
VL  - 24
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study which examined the nature of the managerial work of local government managers in New York City. A questionnaire was sent to all New York City managers to determine the managers? managerial tasks. About 95 percent of the questionnaires were returned from managers employed in 60 different agencies ranging in size. Analysis of the tasks showed 57 common managerial activities that could be divided into six categories; supervision of employees, interpersonal relations, information management, analysis of data, change initiating, and monitoring.
AB  - The article presents a study which examined the nature of the managerial work of local government managers in New York City. A questionnaire was sent to all New York City managers to determine the managers? managerial tasks. About 95 percent of the questionnaires were returned from managers employed in 60 different agencies ranging in size. Analysis of the tasks showed 57 common managerial activities that could be divided into six categories; supervision of employees, interpersonal relations, information management, analysis of data, change initiating, and monitoring.
