T1  - Realistic Job Previews and the Adjustment of New Employees
AU  - Dugoni, Bernard L.
AU  - Ilgen, Daniel R.
Y1  - 1981/09/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255576
DO  - 10.5465/255576
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 579
EP  - 591
VL  - 24
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The study investigated three possible psychological processes underlying the use of realistic job previews (RJPs). RJPs were hypothesized to reduce turnover through (1) lowered expectations and increased job satisfaction, (2) improved ability to cope with unpleasant job circumstances, and (3) the creation of a perceptual set of greater openness and honesty within the company. None of the hypotheses received strong support.
AB  - The study investigated three possible psychological processes underlying the use of realistic job previews (RJPs). RJPs were hypothesized to reduce turnover through (1) lowered expectations and increased job satisfaction, (2) improved ability to cope with unpleasant job circumstances, and (3) the creation of a perceptual set of greater openness and honesty within the company. None of the hypotheses received strong support.
